<div id="outline-container-org168a568" class="outline-2">
<h2 id="org168a568"><span class="section-number-2">1.</span> til</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-1">
<p>
Learned a handful of nifty claude things today.
</p>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-org487ca1c" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org487ca1c"><span class="section-number-3">1.1.</span> <code>/powerup</code></h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-1-1">
<p>
has a great set of bite-sized tips for leveling up your claude game.
</p>
</div>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-org5ecbad1" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org5ecbad1"><span class="section-number-3">1.2.</span> <code>/rewind</code></h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-1-2">
<p>
(which I'd already been using the past couple weeks) has a
handy <code>Esc-Esc</code> keybinding. I actually requently use this simply as
a means of briefly reviewing the prompt history to see where we're
at in the conversation. <code>Esc-Esc</code>, then <code>Esc</code> again to bounce out.
</p>
</div>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-orge1f6f43" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="orge1f6f43"><span class="section-number-3">1.3.</span> <code>/branch</code></h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-1-3">
<p>
This is a new one for me. Seems like it could be really
powerful in tandem with the <code>rewind</code>-heavy workflow I've been using
recently for product and design discovery.
</p>
</div>
